Someone came to fix the floor in my kitchen, so I'm going to pretend I still have a job and work from home while reviewing Too Hot to Handle.
If I can just open this damned file. (Damn OneDrive.)
*pirate voice* I'm in.
And that's when he starts drilling really hard. Great!
His passive-aggressive way of cranking my air purifier to full makes me uncomfortable, but it smells like sawdust, so it's justified even though it's an anti-mask. Plus, I really need to protect myself, right??
I really want to go back to bed, but I can't until he leaves.
The good thing is, I've finished re-reading chapter 4!
Chapter five is long, but there's a lot of suspense. Good work.
Doing find-and-replace on … ➡️ ellipsis character, and there are 54 in this chapter 😅
But anyway, I'm sticking with it. The most natural speeches are usually fragmented, especially when people let themselves go with their emotions.
The craftsman is vacuuming, and with any luck, he'll be done soon.
He went out (as far as I can hear) to cut something. So I took a look to see where he was. It's far from being done :(
Only 7 pages left on chapter five. It remains my favorite chapter, and it's quite well developed. Some layout changes, and minor changes to switch to active voice and improve conciseness. That said, I'd really like a break and a cup of tea, but the guy is still tinkering in my kitchen.
He just started vacuuming again. I hope that's a good sign.
The craftsman is gone!
He told me he had done an estimate for the whole floor, but the homeowners were cheap and only paid for the small damaged area near the door. It's clearly better.
The house is airing out, and my air purifier is running in the kitchen while I enjoy a cup of tea in the garden!
